==Reception==

===Box office===
''The Mummy'' opened on May 7, 1999, and grossed [[USD]] $43 million in 3,210 theaters in the United States on its opening weekend. The film went on to gross $415 million worldwide (Domestic: $155 million; Foreign: $260 million).<ref>{{cite web|title=''The Mummy''|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=mummy.htm|accessdate=2006-11-28}}</ref>

===Critical reaction===
''The Mummy'' received mixed reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite news | last=Welkos | first=Robert W. | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/may/11/entertainment/ca-35903 | title='Mummy' Brings Sunshine to Universal | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=May 11, 1999 | accessdate=December 9, 2014 }}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film holds a 55% rating, based on 83 reviews, with an average rating of 5.7/10. The site's critical consensus reads, "It's difficult to make a persuasive argument for ''The Mummy'' as any kind of meaningful cinematic achievement, but it's undeniably fun to watch."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1087270-mummy/|title=The Mummy|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=2014-12-09}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a score of 48 out of 100, based on 34 critics, indicating "mixed or average reviews"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-mummy|title=The Mummy: Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=2007-06-24}}</ref> 

[[Roger Ebert]], a film critic of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', gave the film 3 out of 4 stars, writing "There is hardly a thing I can say in its favor, except that I was cheered by nearly every minute of it. I cannot argue for the script, the direction, the acting or even the mummy, but I can say that I was not bored and sometimes I was unreasonably pleased."<ref>{{cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=''The Mummy''|publisher=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|date=1999-05-07|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19990507/REVIEWS/905070303/1023|accessdate=2006-11-29}}</ref> Likewise, [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a "B-" grade and said, "''The Mummy'' would like to make you shudder, but it tries to do so without ever letting go of its jocular inconsequentiality."<ref>{{cite news|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|title=''The Mummy''|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=May 7, 1999|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,64020,00.html|accessdate=2006-12-19}}</ref> Bob Graham of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' gave the film high marks for the acting as well as the special effects.<ref>{{cite news|author=Graham, Bob|title='Mummy' -- It's Alive|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle|date=1999-05-07|accessdate=2008-02-03}}</ref>

[[Stephen Holden]] from ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote, "This version of ''The Mummy'' has no pretenses to be anything other than a gaudy comic video game splashed onto the screen. Think ''Raiders of the Lost Ark'' with cartoon characters, no coherent story line and lavish but cheesy special effects. Think ''Night of the Living Dead'' stripped of genuine horror and restaged as an Egyptian-theme Halloween pageant. Think ''Abbott and Costello Meet the Mummy'' grafted onto a [[Bing Crosby]]-[[Bob Hope]] road picture (''The Road to Hamunaptra''?) and pumped up into an epic-size genre spoof."<ref>{{cite news|last=Holden|first=Stephen|title=Sarcophagus, Be Gone: Night of the Living Undead|publisher=The New York Times|date=May 7, 1999|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06E0D7103CF934A35756C0A96F958260&scp=3&sq=The+Mummy&st=nyt|accessdate=2006-11-29}}</ref> Publications like ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'' and ''[[Dallas Observer]]'' came to the conclusion that despite good acting and special effects, the movie lacked cohesion;<ref name=observer/><ref>{{cite news|author=Savlov, Mark|title=The Mummy|publisher=[[The Austin Chronicle]]|date=1999-05-07|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Calendar/Film?Film=oid%3A142860|accessdate=2008-03-12}}</ref> talking about the special effects, the ''Observer'' lamented "If only generating a soul for the film itself were so easy."<ref name=observer>{{cite news|author=Hinson, Hal|url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/1999-05-13/film/mummy-dearest/|title=Mummy dearest|publisher=[[Dallas Observer]]|date=1999-05-07|accessdate=2008-03-20}}</ref> Other publications such as ''[[Jump Cut (journal)|Jump Cut]]'' felt that Industrial Light and Magic's lock on special effects proved detrimental to ''The Mummy''; "The mummy", Ernest Larson wrote for the ''Jump Cut'', "is standard-issue I.L.&M.".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Ernest|last=Larsen|title=The Mummy: traffic in mummies|journal=[[Jump Cut (journal)|Jump Cut]]|url=http://ejumpcut.org/archive/onlinessays/JC43folder/Mummy.html|date=July 2000| issue=43|pages=12<U+2013>15, 128 |accessdate=2008-04-09}}</ref> Kim Newman of the [[British Film Institute]] judged the picture inferior to the original, as all the time was spent on special effects, instead of creating the atmosphere which made the original film such a classic.<ref name="bfi"/> ''[[USA Today]]'' gave the film two out of four stars and felt that it was "not free of stereotypes",<ref name="usa today"/> a sentiment with which the [[British Film Institute|BFI]] concurred.<ref name="bfi">{{cite web|author=Newman, Kim|date=1999-06-01|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/sightandsound/review/152|title=Sight and Sound: The Mummy|work=[[British Film Institute]]|accessdate=2008-04-04}}</ref> "If someone complains of a foul odor, you can be sure an Arab stooge is about to enter a scene. Fraser, equally quick with weapon, fist or quip, may save the day, but even he can't save the picture", ''USA Today'' wrote.<ref name="usa today">{{cite news|last=Wloszczyna|first=Susan|title=Effects New Curse of ''The Mummy''|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=May 7, 1999 }}</ref>

