== Adaptations ==
[[Image:Mummy the Ride.jpg|thumb|right|The entrance to ''[[Revenge of the Mummy (Hollywood)|Revenge of the Mummy]]'' at Universal Studios Hollywood.]]
''The Mummy''{{'}}s box office performance led to numerous sequels and spinoffs. In 2001, the sequel ''[[The Mummy Returns]]'' was released; the film features most of the surviving principal characters, as a married Rick and Evelyn confront Imhotep and the [[Mathayus (Scorpion King)|Scorpion King]].<ref name="rolling stone- mummy return"/> The film also introduced the heroes' son, [[Characters related to The Mummy#Alexander 'Alex' O'Connell|Alex]].<ref name="rolling stone- mummy return">{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/movie/5949327/review/5949328/the_mummy_returns|title=The Mummy Returns|author=Travers, Peter|date=2001-05-09|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=2008-04-01|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071203140113/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/movie/5949327/review/5949328/the_mummy_returns |archivedate = December 3, 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref> The two films inspired both an [[The Mummy: The Animated Series|animated series]] which lasted two seasons, and a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] prequel, ''[[The Scorpion King]]'' (2002), telling the story of the Akkadian warrior as he was crowned king.

A second sequel, called ''[[The Mummy: Tomb of the Dragon Emperor]]'', was released on August 1, 2008. The story takes place in China with the ''Terracotta Emperor'' inspiring the villain, while Rachel Weisz was replaced with [[Maria Bello]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Garrett, Diane|author2=Fleming, Michael  |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117962923.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=Fraser returns for 'Mummy 3'|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2007-04-11|accessdate=2007-04-12 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Fleming, Michael|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117964831.html?categoryid=13&cs=1|title=Bello replaces Weisz in 'Mummy'|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2007-05-13|accessdate=2007-05-13 }}</ref> A prequel to ''The Scorpion King'', ''[[The Scorpion King 2: Rise of a Warrior]]'', was released [[direct-to-DVD]]. Both films were poorly received by critics.

Two video game adaptations of ''The Mummy'' were published by [[Konami]] and [[Vivendi Games|Universal Interactive]] in 2000: an [[Action game|Action]] [[Adventure game|Adventure]] for the [[PlayStation]] and [[Personal computer game|PC]] developed by [[Rebellion Developments]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://psx.ign.com/objects/014/014640.html|title=The Mummy (PSX)|publisher=IGN|accessdate=2008-02-21}}</ref> as well as a [[Game Boy Color]] [[puzzle game]] developed by Konami Nagoya.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/gbc/action/mummy/index.html|title=The Mummy (GBC)|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=2008-02-21}}</ref> The film also inspired a [[roller coaster]], ''Revenge of the Mummy'' in three [[Universal Studios Theme Parks]]: [[Revenge of the Mummy (Hollywood)|Hollywood, California]]; [[Revenge of the Mummy (Florida)|Orlando, Florida]]; and [[Revenge of the Mummy (Universal Studios Singapore)|Sentosa, Singapore]]. On April 4, 2012, Universal announced their plans to [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]] the franchise.<ref>Kroll, Justin, Snieder, Jeff, [http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118052291 "U sets 'Mummy' reboot with Spaihts"], Variety.com, Published 2012-04-04, Retrieved 2012-05-04.</ref>

